{
  "The most movable type of joint is:": "",
  "Synovial": "",
  "Fibrous": "",
  "Sutural": "",
  "Cartilaginous": "",
  "Synovial joints are freely movable (diarthrotic) joints that contain a joint cavity filled with synovial fluid, allowing the greatest range and variety of movement.": "",
  "Skull sutures are examples of which type of joint?": "",
  "Hinge": "",
  "Skull sutures are fibrous joints (synarthroses) where bones are connected by dense fibrous connective tissue. They are essentially immovable in adults, providing strong protection for the brain.": "",
  "The elbow is classified as what type of synovial joint?": "",
  "Ball-and-socket": "",
  "Gliding": "",
  "Pivot": "",
  "The elbow is a hinge joint that allows movement in one plane only: flexion (bending) and extension (straightening), similar to the hinge on a door.": "",
  "The shoulder joint is classified as a:": "",
  "Hinge joint": "",
  "Pivot joint": "",
  "Ball-and-socket joint": "",
  "Saddle joint": "",
  "The shoulder (glenohumeral) joint is a ball-and-socket joint where the spherical head of the humerus fits into the glenoid cavity of the scapula, allowing the greatest range of motion of any joint in the body.": "",
  "Ligaments connect:": "",
  "Muscle to bone": "",
  "Nerve to muscle": "",
  "Muscle to muscle": "",
  "Bone to bone": "",
  "Ligaments are strong bands of dense regular connective tissue that connect bone to bone across a joint, providing stability and limiting excessive movement that could cause injury.": "",
  "Tendons connect:": "",
  "Bone to cartilage": "",
  "Nerve to nerve": "",
  "Tendons are strong cords of dense regular connective tissue that attach skeletal muscles to bones, transmitting the force of muscle contraction to produce movement at joints.": "",
  "Abduction moves a limb:": "",
  "Away from the midline of the body": "",
  "Backward": "",
  "Toward the midline of the body": "",
  "Forward": "",
  "Abduction is the movement of a limb or body part away from the midline of the body, such as raising your arm out to the side. The prefix 'ab-' means 'away from.'": "",
  "The atlas-axis (C1-C2) joint is classified as a:": "",
  "The atlantoaxial joint is a pivot joint where the atlas (C1) rotates around the dens (odontoid process) of the axis (C2), allowing the rotational movement of the head as when shaking your head 'no.'": "",
  "The thumb joint (1st carpometacarpal) is classified as a:": "",
  "The first carpometacarpal joint of the thumb is a saddle joint, where the concave and convex surfaces of the trapezium and first metacarpal interlock. This unique design allows the thumb to oppose the other fingers.": "",
  "A sprain involves damage to:": "",
  "Ligaments": "",
  "Bone": "",
  "Nerves only": "",
  "Muscle": "",
  "A sprain is the stretching or tearing of a ligament, which connects bone to bone at a joint. Common sprain sites include the ankle, knee, and wrist.": "",
  "What is flexion?": "",
  "Moving a limb away from the body's midline": "",
  "Straightening a joint to increase the angle between bones": "",
  "Bending a joint to decrease the angle between bones": "",
  "Rotating a bone around its own long axis": "",
  "Flexion is a movement that decreases the angle between two body parts at a joint, such as bending the elbow to bring the forearm closer to the upper arm.": "",
  "What is extension?": "",
  "Moving a limb toward the body's midline": "",
  "Turning a bone around its axis": "",
  "Extension is a movement that increases the angle between two body parts at a joint, such as straightening the elbow. Extension is typically the opposite of flexion and returns a body part to the anatomical position.": "",
  "What is adduction?": "",
  "Movement of a limb away from the midline": "",
  "Movement of a limb toward the midline of the body": "",
  "Circular movement of a limb": "",
  "Turning the palm downward": "",
  "Adduction is the movement of a limb or body part toward the midline of the body, such as bringing a raised arm back to the side. The prefix 'ad-' means 'toward.'": "",
  "What is pronation?": "",
  "Turning the palm to face upward or anteriorly": "",
  "Bending the foot upward toward the shin": "",
  "Rotation of the forearm that turns the palm to face downward or posteriorly": "",
  "Moving the jaw forward": "",
  "Pronation is the rotation of the forearm so that the palm faces posteriorly (downward when the arm is extended). During pronation, the radius crosses over the ulna.": "",
  "What is supination?": "",
  "Pointing the toes downward": "",
  "Turning the palm to face downward or posteriorly": "",
  "Rotation of the forearm that turns the palm to face anteriorly or upward": "",
  "Bending the wrist laterally": "",
  "Supination is the rotation of the forearm so that the palm faces anteriorly (upward when the arm is extended). This is the position of the forearm in the standard anatomical position. A helpful mnemonic is that you can hold a bowl of soup with a supinated hand.": "",
  "What is circumduction?": "",
  "Sliding movement between flat bone surfaces": "",
  "Rotation of a bone around its own axis": "",
  "Straight-line movement in one plane": "",
  "A cone-shaped movement combining flexion, abduction, extension, and adduction in sequence": "",
  "Circumduction is a complex movement in which the distal end of a limb traces a circle while the proximal end remains relatively fixed. It combines flexion, abduction, extension, and adduction in a continuous sequence, producing a cone-shaped path.": "",
  "What is a synovial joint?": "",
  "A joint connected by fibrous tissue that allows no movement": "",
  "Any connection point between two bones": "",
  "A joint connected only by cartilage that allows slight movement": "",
  "A freely movable joint with a fluid-filled joint cavity, articular cartilage, and a synovial membrane": "",
  "A synovial joint is the most common and most movable type of joint, characterized by a joint cavity enclosed by a synovial membrane that secretes synovial fluid, articular cartilage on bone surfaces, and reinforcing ligaments.": "",
  "What is rotation as a joint movement?": "",
  "Bending a joint to decrease the angle": "",
  "Moving a limb away from the midline": "",
  "The turning of a bone around its own longitudinal axis": "",
  "Gliding one bone surface over another": "",
  "Rotation is the turning of a bone around its own longitudinal axis without lateral displacement. An example is turning your head from side to side or rotating the humerus to turn the forearm inward or outward.": "",
  "What does arthritis mean?": "",
  "Excessive movement at a joint": "",
  "Fusion of two bones at a joint": "",
  "Inflammation of a joint": "",
  "A fracture within a joint": "",
  "Arthritis literally means 'joint inflammation' (from Greek 'arthron' = joint + 'itis' = inflammation). It is a general term for a group of over 100 conditions characterized by joint pain, swelling, and stiffness.": "",
  "What does synovial fluid do?": "",
  "It connects bones across a joint": "",
  "It lubricates the joint surfaces, reduces friction, and nourishes the articular cartilage": "",
  "It produces blood cells within the joint": "",
  "It hardens to form bone during joint replacement": "",
  "Synovial fluid is a viscous, slippery fluid produced by the synovial membrane that lines the joint cavity. It reduces friction between articular cartilage surfaces during movement and supplies nutrients to the avascular cartilage.": "",
  "A soccer player is tackled from the side, and her knee is forced inward. She hears a popping sound and experiences immediate swelling. The orthopedic surgeon suspects damage to the ligament on the medial side of the knee. Which ligament is most likely torn?": "",
  "Anterior cruciate ligament (ACL)": "",
  "Lateral collateral ligament (LCL)": "",
  "Medial collateral ligament (MCL)": "",
  "Posterior cruciate ligament (PCL)": "",
  "A blow to the lateral side of the knee that forces it inward stretches and can tear the medial collateral ligament (MCL). This is one of the most common knee injuries in contact sports because the MCL resists valgus (inward) stress.": "",
  "A patient with rheumatoid arthritis complains that her finger joints are swollen, warm, and stiff, especially in the morning. Her physician explains that her immune system is attacking a specific membrane in her joints. Which structure is the immune system targeting?": "",
  "The tendons crossing the joint": "",
  "The synovial membrane lining the joint cavity": "",
  "The articular cartilage": "",
  "The periosteum around the joint": "",
  "Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks the synovial membrane, causing inflammation (synovitis), joint swelling, and eventually destruction of the articular cartilage and underlying bone.": "",
  "A physical therapist asks a patient to rotate her forearm so that the palm faces the ceiling. The patient then rotates the forearm so the palm faces the floor. What two movements did the patient just perform, in order?": "",
  "Flexion then extension": "",
  "Pronation then supination": "",
  "Supination then pronation": "",
  "Abduction then adduction": "",
  "Supination turns the palm upward (toward the ceiling), while pronation turns the palm downward (toward the floor). The patient first supinated (palm up) then pronated (palm down).": "",
  "A gymnast performs an arm circle while doing a warm-up. Her arm moves in a complete cone-shaped pattern starting from the shoulder joint. Which movement best describes this motion?": "",
  "Flexion followed by extension": "",
  "Rotation": "",
  "Circumduction": "",
  "Abduction only": "",
  "Circumduction is the cone-shaped movement of a limb where the distal end traces a circle while the proximal end remains relatively fixed. It is a combination of flexion, abduction, extension, and adduction occurring in sequence at the shoulder joint.": "",
  "A construction worker develops pain at the base of his thumb after years of repetitive gripping. His doctor explains that the joint at the base of the thumb has a unique shape that allows opposition but also makes it susceptible to arthritis. What type of joint is at the base of the thumb?": "",
  "The first carpometacarpal joint at the base of the thumb is a saddle joint, where the reciprocal concave-convex surfaces allow the thumb to move in multiple planes including opposition. Years of repetitive use can wear down this joint, leading to basal thumb arthritis.": "",
  "A basketball player sprains her ankle by rolling it inward. The team physician explains that a sprain involves damage to a specific type of connective tissue. What tissue was damaged, and what is its normal function?": "",
  "The synovial membrane was damaged; it normally produces synovial fluid": "",
  "Ligaments were damaged; they normally connect bone to bone and stabilize the joint": "",
  "Articular cartilage was damaged; it normally cushions the joint": "",
  "Tendons were damaged; they normally connect muscle to bone": "",
  "A sprain is the stretching or tearing of ligaments, the strong connective tissue bands that connect bone to bone across a joint. Ankle sprains typically involve the lateral ligaments when the foot rolls inward (inversion).": "",
  "A patient tells her doctor she cannot turn her head to check her blind spot while driving. The physician suspects a problem with the joint between C1 and C2. What type of movement does this joint normally allow?": "",
  "Flexion and extension (nodding)": "",
  "Lateral flexion (tilting the head side to side)": "",
  "Circumduction of the head": "",
  "Rotation of the head (turning side to side)": "",
  "The atlantoaxial (C1-C2) joint is a pivot joint that allows approximately 50% of the total rotation of the cervical spine. The atlas rotates around the dens of the axis, enabling the head to turn side to side as when looking over your shoulder.": "",
  "An elderly patient with severe osteoarthritis of the knee has difficulty walking because the articular cartilage has worn away almost completely. His orthopedic surgeon recommends a total knee replacement. What is the primary function of the articular cartilage that has been lost?": "",
  "To connect the femur to the tibia": "",
  "To supply blood to the bones forming the joint": "",
  "To produce synovial fluid for the joint": "",
  "To provide a smooth, low-friction surface and absorb shock at the joint": "",
  "Articular cartilage provides a smooth, nearly frictionless surface for joint movement and absorbs compressive forces. When this cartilage is lost in osteoarthritis, bone grinds against bone, causing pain, inflammation, and limited movement.": "",
  "A yoga instructor is demonstrating a stretch where she raises her straight leg out to the side at the hip, then brings it back across the midline of her body. A student asks which joint movements she is performing. What is the correct answer?": "",
  "Internal rotation then external rotation": "",
  "Raising the leg out to the side is abduction (moving away from the midline), and bringing it back across the midline is adduction (moving toward the midline). These are movements in the frontal (coronal) plane at the hip joint.": "",
  "A patient who had a stroke has lost the ability to use her right hand to grasp objects. Her neurologist explains that grasping requires the thumb to oppose the other fingers, which depends on a specific joint type. What joint type makes human thumb opposition possible?": "",
  "The condyloid joints of the metacarpophalangeal joints": "",
  "The saddle joint of the first carpometacarpal joint": "",
  "The gliding joints of the intercarpal joints": "",
  "The hinge joints of the interphalangeal joints": "",
  "The ability to oppose the thumb to the other fingers, which is essential for grasping, depends on the saddle joint at the base of the thumb. This joint's unique reciprocal concave-convex surfaces allow the multi-directional movement needed for opposition.": ""
}